                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d136">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/448: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Chefoo</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Roberts</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chefoo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-12-29T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 29, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 29—11:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 4, December 15, 1 p.m., Standard
                    Vacuum Oil Company and Texas Oil Company report local sales are increasing due
                    to the fact that small quantities of petroleum products are leaving Chefoo
                    overland for interior. The Asiatic Petroleum Company, a British corporation,
                    reports two shipments have been held up by the authorities. The American
                    companies find inland dealers are not ordering kerosene at Chefoo as there
                    appears to be ample supplies of contraband oil, probably from Dairen, in their
                    possession, selling below prices here.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Tsingtao, and Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Roberts</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
